3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX funding rates are determined by the imbalance between long and short positions rather than perpetual-spot price differences. The protocol charges or pays funding every hour based on which side has more open interest. Oracle pricing from Chainlink eliminates the traditional mark-to-index funding component. Traders on the crowded side pay funding to the less crowded side, creating natural rebalancing incentives."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","AVAX","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX/USDT on GMX benefits from substantial retail interest in Avalanche ecosystem tokens, often creating pronounced long/short imbalances. The pair typically shows higher funding rate volatility compared to major assets due to AVAX's price sensitivity and narrative-driven trading patterns. Cross-chain arbitrage opportunities emerge when funding rates diverge significantly from Binance, Bybit, and other centralized venues."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"AVAX/USDT funding rates on GMX have historically ranged from -0.5% to +2.0% per hour during major Avalanche ecosystem events or market volatility. The pair frequently experiences prolonged periods of positive funding during AVAX bull runs as retail traders maintain heavy long bias. Funding rate spikes typically coincide with subnet launches, major DeFi protocol deployments on Avalanche, or broader L1 narrative cycles. The oracle-based system tends to produce more extreme funding rates compared to order book exchanges during high volatility periods."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The most profitable AVAX arbitrage opportunities occur when GMX funding diverges by more than 0.3% from centralized exchanges like Binance or OKX. Traders can exploit GMX's hourly funding frequency by entering positions just after funding payments to maximize time value. Cross-chain arbitrage requires bridging considerations between Arbitrum and other networks, typically adding 10-30 minutes to position setup. The lack of traditional funding rate caps on GMX can create exceptional arbitrage windows during extreme market conditions."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX's oracle dependency introduces unique risks as Chainlink price feeds can lag during extreme volatility, potentially affecting position PnL accuracy. The GLP pool model means liquidity can become constrained during high utilization periods, increasing price impact costs. Traders must account for higher base fees (0.05% maker/0.07% taker) compared to traditional exchanges when calculating arbitrage profitability. Arbitrum network congestion during high activity can delay position adjustments and funding rate changes."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does GMX calculate AVAX/USDT funding rates?","answer":"GMX calculates and applies funding rates every hour for AVAX/USDT perpetuals. This higher frequency compared to the standard 8-hour funding on most exchanges creates more opportunities for short-term arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"What causes AVAX funding rate spikes on GMX?","answer":"AVAX funding spikes typically result from heavy long bias during Avalanche ecosystem developments, subnet launches, or broader L1 token rallies. The oracle-based system amplifies these imbalances compared to order book exchanges with natural price discovery."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage GMX AVAX funding with other exchanges?","answer":"Yes, cross-exchange arbitrage is possible by taking opposite positions on GMX versus centralized exchanges like Binance or Bybit. Consider bridge times between Arbitrum and other chains when planning position timing and risk management."},{"question":"What are the main risks of GMX AVAX arbitrage?","answer":"Key risks include oracle price lag during volatility, GLP liquidity constraints affecting execution, higher DEX fees eating into profits, and potential Arbitrum network congestion affecting position management timing."}]}]
